{{Infobox organization | name = European Regions Airline Association | former name = {{nobreak|European Regional Airlines Association}} | image = | image_border = | size = <!-- default 200px --> | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | map = <!-- optional --> | msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 250px --> | malt = <!-- map alt text --> | mcaption = <!-- optional --> | map2 = | abbreviation = | motto = | predecessor = | successor = | formation = 1980 | extinction = | merger = | merged = | type = [[trade association]] | status = | purpose = | headquarters = [[Lightwater]], [[Surrey]], United Kingdom | location = | coords = | region_served = Europe | membership = European [[regional airline]]s | language = | general = | leader_title = | leader_name = | leader_title2 = | leader_name2 = | leader_title3 = | leader_name3 = | leader_title4 = | leader_name4 = | key_people = | main_organ = | parent_organization = | affiliations = | budget = | num_staff = | num_volunteers = | website = {{url|www.eraa.org}} | remarks = | logo =European Regions Airline Association logo.png }}
The '''European Regions Airline Association''' is the principal [[trade association]] representing intra-European [[regional airline]]s. It represents 52 airlines and 139 service providers (2017).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eraa.org/about/overview|title=Overview and vision|website=Eraa.org|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>
== History == The European Regions Airline Association was founded as the '''European Regional Airlines Association''' in 1980, by a small number of what were then known as ''commuter airlines''.{{r|gbr|page=127}} The association is registered as a limited company in England & Wales.{{r|self}}
In the 2000s, the line between low-cost airlines serving regional airports close to high-traffic areas and actual regional airlines became blurry, and the scope of ERA's potential members grew much bigger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/regionals-face-competition-from-low-cost-airlines-218493/|title=Regionals face competition from low-cost airlines|website=Flightglobal.com|date=12 October 2007|author=Victoria Moores|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> The congestion of major airports also led to a greater usage of closeby regional airports, once again making ERA a central actor of this growth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/727359/The-rise-and-rise-of-the-regional-airport.html|title=The rise and rise of the regional airport|website=Telegraph.co.uk|date=29 April 2003|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>
In March 2007, the ERA opposed the application of the European commission's rule to increase the airlines' responsibility regarding delayed or cancelled flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/barrot-air-passengers-get-raw-deal/|title=Barrot: air passengers get raw deal|website=Politico.eu|date=28 March 2007|author=Lorraine Mallinder|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>
In May 2008, when the European commission allowed airlines to trade take-off and landing slots, the ERA warned that this could lead to a slot-bartering economy that may in turn deteriorate the primary focus of airlines, servicing passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/transport/news/eu-to-allow-sale-of-airport-slots/|title=EU to allow sale of airport slots|website=Euractiv.com|date=5 May 2008|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>
In February 2013, along with the [[International Air Transport Association]], the ERA published ''A Blueprint for a Single European Sky'', a set of proposals to strengthen the legislative basis for the [[Single European Sky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aviationpros.com/press_release/10960623/a-step-towards-the-single-european-sky|title=A Step towards the Single European Sky|website=Aviationpros.com|date=13 June 2013|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> In July 2013, when the European commission called for all state subsidies for airports to end within 10 years, the ERA criticized the proposal, arguing that this decision will have a negative impact on the development of regional airlines and airports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ainonline.com/aviation-news/air-transport/2013-07-15/europe-set-stifle-state-aid-airports-and-airlines|title=Europe Set To Stifle State Aid for Airports and Airlines|website=Ainonline.com|date=15 July 2013|author=Charles Alcock|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>
In 2014, the ERA pledged for a hiatus of the [[European Union Emissions Trading System]] until a compromise with other international authorities could be reached.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/awin/eu-ets-stop-clock-scope-extended-till-2016|title=EU ETS ‘Stop-the-Clock’ Scope Extended Till 2016|website=Aviationweek.com|date=17 March 2014|author=Cathy Buyck|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>
== Members == {{colbegin}} * [[Adria Airways]] (since 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelandtourworld.com/news/article/era-celebrate-new-airline-member/|title=ERA celebrate new airline member|website=Travelandtourworld.com|date=3 July 2013|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> * [[Air Iceland Connect]] * [[Air Greenland]] (since 2015)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icenews.is/2015/07/22/air-greenland-becomes-european-regions-airline-association-member/|title=Air Greenland becomes European Regions Airline Association member|website=Icenews.is|date=22 July 2015|author=Erlingur Nordal|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> * [[Air Nostrum]] * [[Air Urga]] * [[APG Airlines]] * ASL Airlines [[ASL Airlines France|France]], [[ASL Airlines Hungary|Hungary]], [[ASL Airlines Ireland|Ireland]], [[ASL Airlines Switzerland|Switzerland]] * [[Astra Airlines]] * [[Atlantic Airways]] * [[Aurigny Air Services]] * [[Avanti Air]] * [[Avion Express]] * [[Bek Air]] * [[Belavia]] (since 2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.belavia.by/company/history/|title=History of the airline|website=Belavia.by|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> * [[Binter Canarias]] * [[Blue Air]] * [[Blue Islands]] * [[BMI Regional]] * [[Braathens]] * [[Carpatair]] * [[Cimber (airline)|Cimber]] * [[CityJet]] * [[Croatia Airlines]] * [[Danish Air Transport]] * [[DOT LT]] * [[Eastern Airways]] * [[Flybe]] * [[Hahn Air Lines]] * [[HOP!]] * [[Jet Time]] * [[Jota Aviation]] * [[KLM Cityhopper]] * [[Luxair Luxembourg Airlines]] * [[Mistral Air]] * [[Montenegro Airlines]] * [[Nordic Regional Airlines]] * [[Nordica (airline)|Nordica]] * [[SATA Air Açores]] * [[Scandinavian Airlines]] (since 2017)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cphpost.dk/news/business/sas-enters-into-regional-airline-alliance.html|title=SAS enters into regional airline alliance|website=Cphpost.dk|date=9 February 2017|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> * [[Sky Express]] * [[SkyWork Airlines]] * [[Stobart Air]] * [[Titan Airways]] * [[Trade Air]] * [[Zimex Aviation]] {{colend}}
== Awards == The European Regions Airline Association makes an annual regional "Airport of the Year" award, which in 2016 was given to [[Southampton Airport]], in [[Hampshire]] in southern England.{{r|echo}}
It also organizes a "European regional airline of the year" award, which was attributed to: *1991: [[Binter Canarias]]<ref name="bintercanarias 117">{{cite web|url=https://www.bintercanarias.com/corporativo/noticias/117/binter-canarias-europe-s-best-regional-airline-2005|title=Binter Canarias, Europe's best regional airline 2005|website=Bintercanarias.com|date=14 October 2005|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref> *1992: [[Binter Canarias]]<ref name="bintercanarias 117"/> *2005: [[Binter Canarias]]<ref name="bintercanarias 117"/> *2016: [[CityJet]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/transport-and-tourism/cityjet-named-european-regional-airline-of-the-year-1.2829727|title=CityJet named European regional airline of the year|website=''Irishtimes.com''|date=14 October 2016|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>
