| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Copyright law of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]
| Life + 70 years

If there are multiple authors, life of last surviving author + 70 years<ref name="UK">[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1988/48 Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988], as amended by s. 5, [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1995/3297/contents/made Duration of Copyright and Rights in Performances Regulations 1995]</ref>{{rp|s. 12}}

For films, life + 70 years for the last to die of: principal director, author of screenplay, author of dialogue, or composer of music specifically created for and used in the film.<ref name="UK"/>{{rp|s. 13B}}
| 70 years if the author is unknown

70 years after release; if not released, 70 years after making (sound recordings).<ref>[http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/copyright-term-for-sound-recordings-increases-from-50-to-70-years-today-in-uk/056584 Copyright term for sound recordings increases from 50 to 70 years today]. ''[[MusicWeek]]'', November 1, 2013.</ref> Recordings which entered the public domain prior to January 1, 2013 are not retroactively covered.

50 years from end of calendar year when the broadcast was first made (broadcasts)<ref name="UK"/>{{rp|s. 14}}
| Yes<ref name="UK"/>{{rp|s. 12, 13}}
